An extreme struggle: MP3 players against mobiles.
We'll advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobile phones can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are sufficient reasons to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the manner of use and on the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive gramophone to put on the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there's in your shelves stuffed vinyl discs, with rock art, jazz or blues, you're probably dreaming at least of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, i.e. compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, just as a fan of Pink Floyd would have a hard time supporting listeners purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is broad.
The life of batteries is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just reading music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the first functions, telephone calls and text sending, it is able to read music and movies, to record them, it has a variable quality camera and can, for example, until it is used for navigation.
And if you take into account Smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no fridge knows how to grill meat and no TV will take photographs, we are almost witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without inconvenience.
The larger the number of functions you use, the greater the interval between two reloads will be reduced.
And the reading of music is one of the most important energy goinfres.
Mobiles that are able to read music for ten to twelve hours are rare, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, music readers (especially the most rudimentary) are much more effective.
In the case of cheap mobiles, expect them to play music only for a few hours.
If, in addition, it happens to you to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second reload for the job - this is even valid for the most expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable, after reloading, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music in mobile.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to take it without reduction, given the minute dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
For readers, you do not need, except iPod, any software.
Simply fill in, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or then the judgment of the user.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, in the way of Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cown, intelligent phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobile have more know-how
In choosing a concrete device, you are especially interested in the life span of the accumulator, memory capacity, quality and type of output of the device and, of course, in the ease of control.
If music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it that for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3s.
Virtually all mobiles are capable of this today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to music formats that the mobile or reader is able to read.
All come to read the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach until you will have this format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices also come to read WMA music.
The AAC (format used by the Apple firm and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Just visit the corresponding operator's (or other provider's) web pages from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason for obtaining a musical motive.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and in most cases it is limited to quick-made radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (either via GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phone on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have on you headphones or a handfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in frames, which have virtually all the mobile phones, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical furniture is their price.
The least expensive normally costs less than three thousand.
For a prize of three four thousand crowns, we can already have a very convenient walkman.
In most cases, however, you will be limited by the lack of output for regular headphones.
The price of the best and best-used phones, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
The readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Truly anyone can assure the command of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the least expensive ones (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the order with that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or of a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a random-connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a swapable memory card slot (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
