A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in Czechia is relatively advanced, our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force classic operators to lower prices.
Maybe it won't be a long time.
We have already mentioned, many times, on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
ČTú (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
As a result of the last steps taken by the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible that Czech prices are kept so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this respect, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Agency (ČTú), who stated on several occasions that there was no room for another operator in Czech Czech Republic, is horrified with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network seems to have no more chance (in fact, at present, it would find only very difficult frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable fall in prices, to which the traditional operators had to react as well.
However, even before the arrival of such party disturbances as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were allowed to be heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there remained room for such operators and that they could be truly successful.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the Virtual Operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let's add that behind Mobilking, there's the Penta financial group, which has, among other things, the U:phone in Czech.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need a lot less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
For example, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers text messages in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, placing on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be possible to walk also at home.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone's spokesman, in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
All the more so that it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Chechnya, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Czech negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said in a phone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in Czech Republic were not, in any case, in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their best to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer field, has not been hiding, for long enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We have a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have been able to move forward in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl's spokesperson.
So perhaps the future is promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we may be able to welcome the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for the moment, his creation is accompanied by complete silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," Vlastimil Sršeň of the Press Department of Telephonika O2, mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specific nature of the Czech market.
The spokesperson for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová stated in a rare agreement with the statement of O2: "We have not registered for the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
She added: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator should appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate within such a limited time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs its attention to the completion of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
That is what we believe means most contributions from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The mobile operators' approach is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profit.
How, then, is it good to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know to hear themselves as larvae in the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, when creating the U:fon, was that exerted by the T-Mobile company.
They demonstrate the information available to the public from the ČTú web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon is ready to serve as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "The competition in the mobile market has also been recently expanded by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the RT mobile market, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would, and above all, make it subject to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
It is not, however, just the attitude of ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in the economic competition in Chechnya.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded for the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not previously presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said in response to our question Kristián Chalupa of the UOHS Department of External Relations.
A statement made in this way would not surprise representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one is taking advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than misleading.
More and more, Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreigners, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
However, pressure towards honest market operation and lower prices are apparently not part of UOHS's interests.
What is really shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of essence strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not noticed any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, none therefore have an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools necessary for the opening up of the mobile market to virtual operators are probably even lacking from the telecommunications regulator," said Chaloupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTU that telecommunications constitutes, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts offer another view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for UOHS that three mobile operators proceed visibly in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, mentioned above) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility for ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, through which UOHS washes its hands.
We have already met this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to introduce the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, an extension of ČTU's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
This, the representatives of UOHS must know it very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can work
However, the operation of some kind of virtual pseudo-operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains unseen.
These are companies publishing their own mobile phone price lists, but they are only partially public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specialized mobile phone services are offered for example by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected candidates.
The magic tower consists of the fact that the company makes it before the operator is a classic company client, which controls a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you mention happened, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we would consider and that could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the society in question," answered our question on this issue Martina Kemrová.
However, it is unlikely that an echo of such an activity would not reach the managers of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them non-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to the real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card on their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary mobile operators' customers."
But that is precisely what should seem strange to ČTú.
In addition, another question is asked at UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that UOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to unveil such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would occur, their contractual conditions forbid it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable decline in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators were trying, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers, were involved.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators deal with this issue in the form of a hot potato that is disposed of by transmitting it to a close target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we can only get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more beneficial than profitable.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the cog.
If the coulisse information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at home, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS can hardly remain impassible in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And perhaps we will cease to call more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov mëj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, a choir interpretation and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremias and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, have a good word, so that we understand the words well, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate next year's 175th anniversary.
For the first time in 1834, Kde domov resounded on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), a Czech original play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
