Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cockroach escapes from danger, does that mean that he also feels afraid?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the "Edge" online magazine, contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, one can at least hope that all human brains present the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the questions of feeling or in general consciousness, we will enter into hard-to-practice lands because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in the face of danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it makes death, escapes or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduct a comparable subjective life.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our life subjective to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated almost always with the human consciousness include the Prefrontal Side Cortex (because of its participation in the short-term memory and leadership and enforcement functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be entirely absent in other beings.
So at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from the other primates.
Another significant feature could be the linguistic nature of humans: a large part of their existence is related to language, which often means that their consciousness depends on them.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if the conscience were not to depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that the animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, is neither measured nor, because of this particular hardware, analyze based on our own experience, then its observation poses great problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of the conscious life, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
