The first time this happens, you may be surprised, but it really doesn't matter.
It's a benign sleep disorder called sleep disorder.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking during the night.
This phenomenon may appear very sporadic (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of severe fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night sickness (wetting) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very severe fevers, stress or overexcitement situations.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or instead with screams, cries, long speeches ...
If sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes much anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We said that it is a benign alteration, so there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep impairment that can be treated (e.g., if it is related to apnea of sleep or stress).
What we can do is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or television series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm indoors.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as sleepwalks appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will no longer remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and then rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because he's asleep, he's not aware to be able to organize his thinking.
In addition, you'll hear what he says, but you won't know what he's dreaming about, then pay attention to the way you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing very bad, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
