Interview - From blood to safety
Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Decary, was right to rejoice because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994 the Government of Canada, in the face of this tragedy and the crowd of the public, conducted a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster to cease to be repeated.
While Judge Krever delayed filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and two territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started his activities, only 38% of people still trusted in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
In an effort to improve the safety of blood products and labour on the ground during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," she said before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94 per cent of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, maintains that "trust is something extremely fragile."
From its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the disease of the mad cow, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, were present in Europe.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known that a serious disease can result from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had been living in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was therefore refused.
However, a few years ago, it was demonstrated beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied had meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique was found in the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs have shorten the silent period, which extends between the moment the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors are infected without knowledge and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products annually, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," said Héma-Québec's head of management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen is going to emerge in the system.
Not later that last year the Chikungunya virus, like the West Nile virus, appeared on the island of Réunion, was transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," continued Dr. Décary, noting that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide adequate supplies.
"Necessaries increase because the population ages.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the blood donor network that on average only 3 per cent of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any person in health who is 18 years of age and over meets the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of those who offer their blood are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is present, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they get older and can no longer give their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today's life is so frightful, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving of his blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These fabrics are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public bank of cord blood in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is covered by a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to collect more than a thousand each year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who described this program for the collection of cord blood as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed that they can't access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
