Libre opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In his September 17 issue, Le Dévoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Vice-President of the Canadian Miner Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has attempted a defamation of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the sound in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamatory prosecutions, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defence and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the practically bottomless pockets of the mining industry.
The tactics, in these unequal struggles, are often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will push the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to reconsider the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are normally done through the exchange of ideas and not by slamming.
It was therefore enough for the mining industry to open its books, records and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can at the same time ask for a "public" debate while disregarding the opinions of the same audience?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to fattening lawyers paid and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What you don't understand - or don't want to understand - Barrick Gold is that the public who supports Black Canada's authors and publishers is doing so primarily because he rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a bâillon chase (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a settlement for the authors of Black Canada inciting them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal speech, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on academic freedom of research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in a bloc, the right to quote credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease rich companies in this world in a country like Canada, under repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada authors.
She has a right to reply.
The academic environment, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's far-reaching pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to her claim, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this type of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan aimed at curbing the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both Houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides: better control by the electors of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of committed public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right to look at salaries paid to the leaders of the aided enterprises.
The US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to sprint in the last few hours out of fear of the effect of a further failure on the mood of investors.
The deadline for opening up the markets was this morning.
The two candidates for the U.S. presidential election, who were later associated with the negotiations, were rather in favour of the agreement, although they did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that they were forced to reach this end.
Senator Democrat Barack Obama has given himself the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that to enable the owners to retain their domicile and that on the salary of the executives of the enterprises rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no way to congratulate them.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American television waves.
Asked about another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I've read show that this is something we're all going to have to digest and with which we're going to be able to move forward.
The option of not doing anything is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700-billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayers' money the suspicious, risk-active and unsold receivables of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the breakdown of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (subprime) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to liquidity freezes and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who had put together the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed to have come out of this deadlock since the Democrats have agreed that some "toxic" assets of the companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision has also been added stating that if the government were to incur losses for five years with this program, it could set up new taxes to help it recover its implementation.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of 250 billion to which an additional 100 billion may be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be endorsed by another vote of the Congress.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will get participation in the aided companies that will be worth dividends in the event of profit and that he can resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and severance allowances paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to the vote of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green fire.
In fact, votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Of course Washington doesn't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, member of the House Finance Committee.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of taking advantage of taxpayers."
Animator of a small group at the Congress known as "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic professors, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to tell us: Congress is asked not to rush and carefully examine the way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis in Europe.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas reported that it had failed to acquire its competitor in full shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (US$2.9 billion) in the crisis of real estate loans at risk in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, a right to vote in the bank and influence is recovered.
It is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that the times are making an announcement of uncertainty."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalizing another bank damaged by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would recover all outstanding loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which more than 41 billion (755 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the British bank's branches and customer accounts.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after the Northern Rock, that the British government should have nationalized since the beginning of this financial crisis.
