What could Zuschlag &amp; Company do in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings will begin in connection with the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damage. Other charges have been held against them, such as false and false use.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from subsidies was spent on personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The state and municipalities' money, about HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand in the banks of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to touch the money of the subsidies obtained by issuing invoices of fees, behind which no actual benefits were provided and thus associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books on the Józsefváros market, while they manufactured the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the Northern Balaton Lake provincial tours, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's statement, he had to find pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on which they made the other invoices they were going to introduce, inter alia, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as to the Municipality of Capital for access to grants.
The majority of invoices were created by István Lados and his complicit András, who, according to our information, were mainly concerned with preparing the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "research circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place restored a group of 90 people, members of the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice established on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will subsequently be named Együtt a Harmadik Évezredert, was guilty of forms and background errors.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
Invoice issuers with overflowing imagination also fell into excess, when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither the name Jobb Jövőért nor that of the Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told the site hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he immediately knew that it was wrong documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a bad place on the cache."
He added: "Aside from the form, the fact that according to the invoice, a hundred people had stayed there, neither did they glue, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much room.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
In addition, there was no information on the travel agencies in Budapest, as part of their choice, but only organizing travel abroad. Thus, in fact, they reported travel in Hungary on cash bills, which is also contrary to the agency's accounting practices.
Overcrowding, as it appeared during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while the travel services, the destination of which is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices established on behalf of the Hotel Revfülöp in the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's benefits do not support a 25% VAT as indicated, but a 15% VAT. Furthermore, the hotel's employees only issue printed invoices, while the fakes were handwritten.
The prosecutor's investigation reveals that "emitters" also made mistakes by mentioning as a service the carriage of goods by road, that the company issuing invoices could not exercise, since its profile was the investment council.
In addition, it is also for vices of forms, such as types of incorrect invoices and false stamps, that invoices issued in the order of Együtt a Harmadik Évesredert Alapitvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont proved false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó sports internship, both of which refuse to be the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
The fraudsters also paid no attention to the fact that HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group was supposed to have a meal at their home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the company's liquidator refused to issue this invoice.
Deliberate facts
Another category of invoice issuers is that made up of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictional invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapitvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal Group - Ifjú Szocialisták, established an invoice at the order of the Együtt Foundation a Harmadik Évezredert, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of the company Collab Kft. was led to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices in the order of the foundation Jobb Jövőért Alapitvány, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the association Vörösfenyő Egyesület, for an amount of about five million HUF, but behind which no benefits were actually provided.
No financial movement has taken place, either since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this has prevented organizations from mentioning it in their accounts.
The following category of companies issuing invoices is that of companies directly related to the accused.
For example, the CEO of Delta Trió Kft., in charge of fuel and motor vehicle trade, whose headquarters was in Budapest, but where it could be found, was Ivan Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately 18 million HUF.
According to the investigation, these equipment would have been purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been liquidated since 14 September 2005.
The director of the company was a Romanian-born man, to whom Ivan Kubatov would also have submitted documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
According to what we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices in the order of the Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt companies to Harmadik Évezredert Alapitvány, and that he prevented their countervalue.
It was precisely at Ivan Kubatov's request that Romanian masons created Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies worked, which the accused explains because they did not receive work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused as well as editor of the founding acts of the companies, he established invoices in their names, in the order of associations relating to Zushlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generació associations.
Kubatov gave to organizations, 15 total invoices, issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The parquet thought that 10% of the amounts indicated on the invoices and VAT were in Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictional invoices that were used as part of the Biztos Pont grant application.
In January 2006, the Association Y-Generació and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországert filed a grant application with the public utility body of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapitvány (TMA).
They obtained this subsidy for a two-fold amount of HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the objectives indicated in the application.
To avoid this, five fictional invoices received from the Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, it was these invoices that were found during the search carried out in the office of Árpád Kemecsei, in the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, a portion of the accused will report the method of making invoices, as she had done before the prosecutor's office.
What could be really interesting would be that the principal defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil over all history.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has promised several times to tell the least details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or possibly the socialists would have agreed that in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the 50 million HUF, Zusi would bear only the hat.
Today, the latter is likely to be vexed, since the applications for his placement in a supervised residence, on the basis of a lightening of his conditions of detention, are continually falling into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of unreparable economic crimes, walk freely or at least, wait at their own home for the end of the procedure.
The psychology of the auction: why do we spend more money?
During auction sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate merchandise.
The neurology and economics researchers at the University of New York have successfully updated the neurological and economic foundations of this apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distant from this type of competition, such as sales on eBay, which is why they prefer even to pay too high a price.
These researches attempted to develop a neurological pattern of this kind of "play" using sales at the experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played the loto, while the other group participated in a commercial auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging process (MRI) the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the sale at auctions whose essential element is the auction of a third, the whole located under the brain trunk, called striatum, was in an intense way during the loss of the party.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of self-stimulation of the nervous system.
This is why, according to researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight to the violent response of striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
At the same time, three groups oversold a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were winning the party, then they would receive an additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received these $15 before the auctions, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the focus was on one victory, while the other on failure.
By testing the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the player team "against failure" were willing to put higher than those performed by the control group and the "for victory" team.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auction sales only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only the neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation." - noted Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary are 100 miles away, but only seven miles are treated, which is because the patients often do not know they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowish are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g., contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood and organic fluid viruses (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is nevertheless recommended to be vaccinated against A and B viruses. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by a general poor condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white eye a visible yellow, the saddles become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die of the most serious form of this disease, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause of this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to reach the virus, because the pathogen destroys liver cells in a sneezing manner. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion prior to 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a laboratory routine examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor who treats as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the world's day of hepatitis, which was first organized in 2004 by the agencies representing the sick in the four corners of the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to the chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does he who believes in God feel any less pain?
According to recent research results, religious belief would function as some kind of analgesic, which would already have contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article that researchers at Oxford University had an interesting experience in analyzing how belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of the human being.
As part of this experience for the least odd, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers have been able to exclude much of the suffering.
Through a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences involving academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experience is carried out in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and broadcasting electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked participants of the experience to look in a sustained manner two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady to the Hermine painted by Léonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among the believers, while the choice of the painting of Da Vinci, not very different from the first, concerned its soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while looking either at the religious theme painting or the more general theme one.
The Catholics stated that in the eyes of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe", as someone whose "care" they took care of, and they "calmed, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that we can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in the atheists, provided we find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of these research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, effectively change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, is the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if one shows the believers a Madonna painted by Léonard or a painter of the same size?
Would the sight of a better quality Virgin Mary cause better results?
