Intelligent Car Imitates Bourdon Flight · Global Voices
What method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the bourdonating bees gave the strategic idea of departure to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-robotized control system, of the BR23C type, which he equipped with bees qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flight, each bee is its own space, of oval shape, which actually resembles much of our secure protection hull - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The facet eye of the bee plays a vital role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
In order to imitate the functions of the facet eye, the engineers discussed the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor on board, which transforms it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Contrary to any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre takes place in an instinctive manner.
"If it wasn't, the mini robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," says Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where the collision is currently considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid the other bees, in our case, it was only possible to use the rotating movement, acceleration and slowdown as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries that are lighter and the energy concentration is higher, making their life span longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive smart reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the capacity to store.
This mechanism should only treat some incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres. Thus, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a giga-bytes capacity, not even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its entrance into the cars manufactured in series in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
