Industrial prices have continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Office of Statistics of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to those in a previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic prices and exports, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those in the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared with those in the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry have only experienced a slight increase in the order of 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry increased by 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the sectors of supply of electricity, gas, steam and water, representing a significant weight in domestic industrial exploitation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a comparison of twelve months, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, the prices of the oil processing sector have experienced the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the manufacture of metal products, a 13.2 per cent increase in prices was observed, while in the important area of food, beverages and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions were made in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase has increased from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
Throughout the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
The prices of the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent in the previous year.
Among the internal trade groups and according to sector allocation, in August, the investment profit-initiating sectors showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials manufacturing sectors for subsequent processing did not experience changes compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase in energy and materials production sectors was observed for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods sector, 6.8 per cent inflation was measured, while for the benefit-initiating sectors, a 1.4 per cent decrease was measured.
Export sales prices in the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment decreased by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro and 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
