Today, in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities began, the host of which is France, as a representative of the current Presidency of the European Union.
In his message to the plenary assembly, as one of the main spokespersons of the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, MEP Fides European People's Party, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is a violation of the law that affects Roma children most and thus, one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened, on the one hand, by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and on the other, by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
