"A overwhelming majority of Roma youth do not have high school diplomas, and as a result of poor elementary education, only a tiny part has the possibility of obtaining a higher education degree."
Járóka also stressed that education as a basic right of the human being plays a key role in upholding other fundamental rights.
Investment in early education for Roma children means strengthening the economy of the member countries of the European Union.
According to the Euro-Deputy, it is necessary to raise awareness of these relations in the widest possible circle, also between the Roma and non-Roms.
Indeed, the earlier a Roma child begins school, the more he increases his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; by taxes paid from his income and consumption, he participates in the State budget.
"By virtue of their European Union nationality, Roma must be assured of their right to quality education, and be protected from low quality and sectarian education." - said Lívia Járóka.
In the honourable Member's view, there is a need for cooperation from the European Union aimed at an objective, and action is needed to speed up the disintegration process of schools, so compliance with existing anti-discrimination directives and preparation is of paramount importance.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and joblessness. We must give the opportunities provided by democracy to Roma children, so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe" - Járóka demanded.
On behalf of the European Year for Equal Opportunities for All, the aim of the Summit for Equal Opportunities in Europe held each year since the Berlin Summit last year is to provide a unique platform to support measures taken to promote equal opportunities and to combat discrimination at European level and at the level of Member States.
