Mp3 reader pointed at the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listen to full volume music for an extended period using portable music devices such as Mp3 players, can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is announced by the European Commission, which, in a communiqué published in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report - let us read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such an important number of young people who frequently use portable music and mobile phones at full volume can inadvertently damage their hearing in an irreparable way," Meglena Kuneva says.
"According to scientific data, the EU is still at a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this public domain information.
We must also review existing monitoring systems in the light of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music equipment and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"Scientifics-concludes the Executive EU- confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures might possibly be adopted to better protect children and adolescents, against exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but concern increases as regards hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to full volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits of the maximum noise level at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions during extended periods risk permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to approximately 2.5 million and 10 million people in the U.S.
