The elites are in danger.
The phenomenon had already appeared a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a large number of Americans were, and still, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the American economy.
And it is well the New York Times yesterday that confirms it by communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its early East Coast soul, moderate, favourable to federal institutions as well as to business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the Washington Party" and the world of finance, particularly powerful in the states of the Centre and the South.
The soul, precisely, which made itself feel despotically with the vote I was speaking to you at the beginning.
However, what has just been cited is just one example of the changes, the major changes that the current economic earthquake is predicting or already leaves to run: not only to the United States, but throughout the West, and it can be not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the phenomena that have occurred for some time, to such an extent that in the new climate they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the renewal, the extraordinary revival, of the dual sovereign state category, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of financial-banking institutions which, of course, have close relations with abroad, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one State.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of play, or it does not have much to say: the obvious evidence is provided by the European Union, which, as usual, between the various interests and the various national strategies, does not come to a decision on any common political lines.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a feeling of credit: when we go through a difficult period, there are only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in place.
They also have the means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization will ever have in a similar manner.
This new emphasis on the state-of-the-nation crisis is, of course, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the more recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a fairly related factor: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalised finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once that our future will, on the contrary, have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather little material things such as water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but which are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more maps than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably said Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take over the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species that have proved to be inadequate and full of shadows.
And also, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacies, a feeling of alienation that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of countries of the West.
Thus further increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now to their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more foreign to the opinions of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership, fed underground, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "revolutions" or, in the changes of the collective moods of the latter recently, from the conservative ascent in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of the workers in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and it might well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not come by chance).
It is felt that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their intellectuals accredited, their format, would say someone, have ever more difficulty, which does not date today, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and acts potentially in a disproportionate manner.
In view of all this, to speak of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda, it seems frankly exaggerated.
But we say well, keep your eyes wide open, that's not without reason.
The super glue to walk on the walls.
Win the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centres, and today a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to hold a 100-kilogram body on a vertical wall.
The Study- The American journal Science published the findings of some researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nano tubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged as a pile of spaghetti." Explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by geckos' legs, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "detach easily from the wall," explains Liming Dai, researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
MARKING ON MURS? –" this material could be used as a temporary adhesive" adds Liming Dai.
Could it be to walk on the walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of much less fascinating use such as connection between electronic devices, since carbon nano tubes are drivers of heat and electric current.
Other applications could concern aerospace engineering.
For now, no superhero.
