Student victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market doesn't know about crisis
According to the last survey by Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a simple room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding whole categories of young people, the right to study because of the very high global costs that families of origin have to support," explains Sunia's head of study, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand of students has distorted the market so that a generalized increase process has even begun for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also include a series of violations: free-type contracts, not registered, no rent limit, sub-locations.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of taxation are needed to calm prices.
In detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, there is a minimum of 650 euros (Blackband area), at an average value of 800 (Lambate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, an average bed costs 350/400 euros, one room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are required for a single, 450 for a double bed.
Smaller values (550 euros for a simple one) for areas close to other universities (Ostian and Cinecittà).
You can only save yourself if you stay away from the peripheral areas: 300 euros for one bed, and 450 euros for a single one in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, you spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for bed, it is necessary to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rents are often taken by extra community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent requested to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, cities choose historic halls.
The historic cinema halls close in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates what is happening in the large Italian urban centres, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large halls, and the death of consumption of the mono halls in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that we find inevitable and undeniable; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, these are often historical and memory-filled places, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a side of the road and so many emotions" observes the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of the traders, mean everything: over the past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the rooms of the main cities that have paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is leading with 82 cinemas mono halls lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms t that the first responsible for their disappearance is the event of multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-sall cinemas: 195 screens plus in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as Emilia-Romagne.
"Italian exploitation has grown irrationally" notes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it is still necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a living room in a city, these visitors are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit for traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately EUR 10 million.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros a year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between Mayor and Anec, the first of that kind in Italy, to defend and promote mono-room cinemas of the historic centres and the outskirts.
The proposed regulations include tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and special parking rates will be available in some parking lots and parking lots.
"This is an initiative that pleases" observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna setting up other measures.
However, it is clear that in order to contrast the superpower of multiplex, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me, has always been important: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradise Cinema" to which I had already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto, or the Quirinal de Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so much shared emotions, I turn from the other side not to see the blackboards by the dust.
